    <h2 id="why-vitamin-c">Why Collagen Supplements Need Vitamin C</h2>

    <p>Your body doesn't just absorb collagen peptides and paste them into your skin. It breaks them down, uses them as <strong>signaling molecules</strong>, and synthesizes entirely new collagen from scratch using fibroblasts in your dermis. This synthesis process depends critically on two enzymes — <strong>prolyl hydroxylase</strong> and <strong>lysyl hydroxylase</strong> — and both require vitamin C as an enzymatic cofactor. Without adequate vitamin C, these enzymes cannot function, and the collagen peptides you absorb get metabolized into generic amino acids instead of becoming new skin collagen.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>This is why historical scurvy — a vitamin C deficiency — causes catastrophic collagen breakdown: wound healing stops, teeth fall out, and blood vessels collapse. Modern doses are much smaller (just 70-100mg daily prevents deficiency), but the <strong>same biochemistry applies to collagen supplementation</strong>. Your fibroblasts cannot make collagen without vitamin C, even if you flood your system with collagen peptides.</p>
      <cite>American Journal of Clinical Nutrition — vitamin C and collagen synthesis</cite>
    </div>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card"><strong>Enzymatic cofactor</strong><p>Prolyl and lysyl hydroxylase require vitamin C to hydroxylate proline and lysine — essential steps in forming the triple-helix structure of collagen.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><strong>Antioxidant protection</strong><p>Vitamin C also neutralizes free radicals that would otherwise degrade existing collagen fibers, especially from UV exposure.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><strong>Fibroblast stimulation</strong><p>Topical and oral vitamin C stimulate dermal fibroblasts to produce more type I and III collagen.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><strong>RDA: 75-90mg</strong><p>Women need 75mg, men 90mg. Supplementation up to 200mg is safe. Doses above 2,000mg may cause GI upset.</p></div>
    </div>

    <h2 id="how-much">How Much Vitamin C With Collagen?</h2>

    <p><strong>70-100mg of vitamin C daily is sufficient for collagen synthesis.</strong> Doses above 200mg provide no additional collagen benefit because vitamin C is water-soluble and excess is excreted in urine. If your collagen gummy already contains 30-60mg vitamin C, you typically do not need additional supplementation — dietary sources make up the rest.</p>

